1
00:00:04,504 --> 00:00:08,174
<i>The Shiramine serial femicide case.</i>

2
00:00:08,258 --> 00:00:11,010
<i>I ran away from that case.</i>

3
00:00:11,094 --> 00:00:12,679
Please tell me, Professor.

4
00:00:12,762 --> 00:00:13,930
What really happened?

5
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:17,767
I want him to be able to forget everything
and pass away in peace.

6
00:00:17,851 --> 00:00:19,519
Ota from the Public Prosecutor's Office.

7
00:00:19,602 --> 00:00:21,730
I heard you went to see Dr. Kujo?

8
00:00:22,313 --> 00:00:26,651
This could be a piece of a bigger puzzle.

9
00:01:01,144 --> 00:01:02,729
I am a forensic pathologist.

10
00:01:03,313 --> 00:01:06,608
My name is Masumi Mizusawa.

11
00:01:14,491 --> 00:01:19,704
I served as Professor Kujo's assistant
during the forensic investigation

12
00:01:20,663 --> 00:01:24,125
of the Shiramine serial femicide case.

13
00:01:29,672 --> 00:01:31,424
What's the point now?

14
00:01:38,723 --> 00:01:40,225
I am very sorry.

15
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:47,148
Fifteen years ago,

16
00:01:48,608 --> 00:01:49,818
I…

17
00:01:51,402 --> 00:01:53,113
ran away from that case.

18
00:01:53,822 --> 00:01:56,783
Even though I had doubts
about the investigation results…

19
00:02:00,286 --> 00:02:03,331
I want to uncover the truth
behind that case.

20
00:02:04,374 --> 00:02:06,251
That is why

21
00:02:07,085 --> 00:02:08,503
I came here today.

22
00:02:11,881 --> 00:02:15,635
Could you please
tell me what happened back then

23
00:02:16,678 --> 00:02:19,013
just one more time?

24
00:02:28,481 --> 00:02:30,150
It has been 15 years, you know.

25
00:02:39,325 --> 00:02:41,786
Stop making a fool out of me.

26
00:02:55,508 --> 00:02:57,302
MINISTRY OF HEALTH, LABOR AND WELFARE

27
00:02:57,385 --> 00:03:00,179
Excuse me.
Here is this week's performance report.

28
00:03:00,263 --> 00:03:01,890
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

29
00:03:02,932 --> 00:03:04,559
<i>Regarding MEJ,</i>

30
00:03:04,642 --> 00:03:07,812
you know how the prosecution
feels about it, right?

31
00:03:07,896 --> 00:03:08,938
I understand.

32
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:10,607
We'll look into their internal affairs.

33
00:03:12,317 --> 00:03:13,276
Sir…

34
00:03:14,319 --> 00:03:15,361
Mr. Yamazaki?

35
00:03:17,363 --> 00:03:19,574
Oh, good work.

36
00:03:25,955 --> 00:03:28,458
Having a baby is hard after all, isn't it?

37
00:03:29,584 --> 00:03:30,877
The nights are tough.

38
00:03:30,960 --> 00:03:32,629
Our little one just won't sleep.

39
00:03:32,712 --> 00:03:33,796
Right, I've heard.

40
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:36,049
That sounds brutal.

41
00:03:37,175 --> 00:03:38,843
Very cute, though.

42
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:42,889
They say children reward you with a
lifetime of joy before they're three.

43
00:03:42,972 --> 00:03:44,974
-Wow.
-I kind of understand that now.

44
00:03:45,058 --> 00:03:47,018
A lifetime of joy, huh?

45
00:03:47,685 --> 00:03:50,313
I haven't seen my parents in a while…

46
00:03:54,859 --> 00:03:57,028
Hello, this is Medical Examiner Japan.

47
00:03:59,155 --> 00:04:02,283
The deceased is 75-year-old Hideo Susaki.

48
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:06,079
A ward official got worried
after Susaki didn't show up for a meeting.

49
00:04:06,162 --> 00:04:08,665
The landlord opened the apartment
with a master key

50
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:10,416
and found him deceased.

51
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:13,169
It appears that three to four days
have passed since his death.

52
00:04:13,253 --> 00:04:14,921
A so-called "lonely death."

53
00:04:15,004 --> 00:04:16,547
They happen a lot lately.

54
00:04:16,631 --> 00:04:20,218
The Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare
is also taking measures,

55
00:04:20,301 --> 00:04:22,428
but the reality is quite difficult.

56
00:04:22,512 --> 00:04:26,140
We know from Susaki's past medical records
that he had chronic conditions

57
00:04:26,224 --> 00:04:28,643
such as heart failure
and high blood pressure.

58
00:04:28,726 --> 00:04:32,647
So that means it was
a natural death, maybe?

59
00:04:32,730 --> 00:04:36,651
Still, the possibility of murder
cannot be ruled out yet.

60
00:04:37,652 --> 00:04:40,405
This was left on the desk.

61
00:04:40,488 --> 00:04:42,323
I WON'T FORGIVE YOU

62
00:04:42,407 --> 00:04:46,119
There's an injury on the back of his head,
probably from hitting it hard.

63
00:04:46,202 --> 00:04:50,206
The police intend to continue
the investigation

64
00:04:50,290 --> 00:04:54,544
under the assumption that Mr. Susaki
was murdered over an altercation.

65
00:04:56,004 --> 00:04:58,589
The wound is a bit old.

66
00:04:59,882 --> 00:05:02,552
We won't know for sure
until we run an accurate test,

67
00:05:02,635 --> 00:05:05,555
but from the state of blood coagulation
around the wound

68
00:05:05,638 --> 00:05:07,932
and the progress of the swelling,

69
00:05:08,016 --> 00:05:11,978
it is highly likely
that this wound was formed a while ago

70
00:05:12,061 --> 00:05:14,439
and was left untreated.

71
00:05:15,064 --> 00:05:16,983
Also, the bodily fluids

72
00:05:17,859 --> 00:05:19,694
have left a rather large mark.

73
00:05:19,777 --> 00:05:21,738
Judging from the condition of the body,

74
00:05:21,821 --> 00:05:24,574
it appears that he was
significantly weakened.

75
00:05:24,657 --> 00:05:26,492
He didn't pass away immediately,

76
00:05:26,576 --> 00:05:29,787
but was likely unable
to move from that spot,

77
00:05:29,871 --> 00:05:32,749
remaining there for a long time
as he grew weaker.

78
00:05:34,042 --> 00:05:38,379
Even so, the body
is now lying near the entrance.

79
00:05:43,760 --> 00:05:44,927
What about his family?

80
00:05:46,429 --> 00:05:49,057
There was no relative
who could be contacted.

81
00:05:49,140 --> 00:05:51,225
Seems like he has no close family.

82
00:05:56,272 --> 00:05:58,024
Twenty-six degrees.

83
00:05:58,107 --> 00:05:58,941
Yes.

84
00:06:00,693 --> 00:06:01,819
Let's begin.

85
00:06:05,198 --> 00:06:08,743
The contusion on the scalp
on the back of his head

86
00:06:08,826 --> 00:06:12,497
seems to have occurred
about two weeks before Susaki passed away.

87
00:06:12,580 --> 00:06:13,498
Furthermore,

88
00:06:13,581 --> 00:06:18,002
there was an abrasion-like wound
all over his right arm below the elbow.

89
00:06:18,086 --> 00:06:20,338
This does not appear to be from a fall.

90
00:06:21,672 --> 00:06:24,467
A chronic subdural hematoma
was also confirmed.

91
00:06:24,550 --> 00:06:29,305
Bleeding occurred inside the brain
after an injury, and slowly grew worse.

92
00:06:30,014 --> 00:06:32,517
With a hematoma of this size,
it is highly likely

93
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:35,812
that he was showing symptoms
of limb paralysis and couldn't walk.

94
00:06:36,354 --> 00:06:41,567
That might be why Mr. Susaki
was unable to move for a long time.

95
00:06:41,651 --> 00:06:45,321
However, the hematoma
is not the direct cause of death.

96
00:06:46,280 --> 00:06:48,658
We found dilation in the left ventricle.

97
00:06:48,741 --> 00:06:51,494
We are now waiting for
the tissue biopsy results.

98
00:06:51,577 --> 00:06:53,704
We'll add chemical testing.

99
00:06:53,788 --> 00:06:55,665
The cause of death is still unknown?

100
00:06:57,250 --> 00:07:02,255
We've observed multiple symptoms,
but none are the decisive cause of death.

101
00:07:02,338 --> 00:07:03,339
What about foul play?

102
00:07:03,422 --> 00:07:05,466
We don't know that yet either.

103
00:07:06,134 --> 00:07:09,137
Why did he collapse near the entrance,

104
00:07:09,720 --> 00:07:11,973
and how did he get the wound
on his right arm?

105
00:07:12,056 --> 00:07:14,350
For now, it's a mystery.

106
00:07:19,522 --> 00:07:21,190
YOSHIMOTO

107
00:07:21,274 --> 00:07:23,276
<i>-Thank you!</i>
<i>-Thank you all!</i>

108
00:07:23,359 --> 00:07:25,820
<i>-That was great applause from you all.</i>
<i>-I know!</i>

109
00:07:26,404 --> 00:07:28,281
<i>Thank you very much!</i>

110
00:07:37,373 --> 00:07:43,171
Why does it get this messy
in just one week?

111
00:07:46,632 --> 00:07:49,135
At least throw the garbage
into the trash can.

112
00:07:49,719 --> 00:07:51,262
I always tell you that, right?

113
00:07:53,014 --> 00:07:54,348
Got it?

114
00:08:00,563 --> 00:08:05,276
I'll make a batch of food again today
and leave it in the fridge.

115
00:08:05,943 --> 00:08:07,153
Make sure to eat it.

116
00:08:08,029 --> 00:08:09,739
Don't worry about it.

117
00:08:13,534 --> 00:08:16,746
I've told you many times
that you don't need to come anymore.

118
00:08:17,538 --> 00:08:19,665
If you collapse all by yourself,

119
00:08:21,375 --> 00:08:23,586
nobody will know, right?

120
00:08:25,671 --> 00:08:27,340
I don't care if that happens.

121
00:08:29,509 --> 00:08:31,093
That's not okay.

122
00:08:33,221 --> 00:08:34,305
I'm going to sleep.

123
00:08:55,284 --> 00:08:56,494
Good morning.

124
00:08:57,537 --> 00:08:58,746
Good morning.

125
00:09:18,182 --> 00:09:22,019
Is there something bothering you
regarding Mr. Susaki's case?

126
00:09:22,520 --> 00:09:23,354
Well…

127
00:09:24,814 --> 00:09:27,149
Somehow, I can see my father in him.

128
00:09:30,194 --> 00:09:31,946
A little while ago,

129
00:09:32,029 --> 00:09:36,409
my father retired from the workplace
where he worked for so long,

130
00:09:37,034 --> 00:09:38,703
and right at that time,

131
00:09:38,786 --> 00:09:41,414
my mother suddenly
passed away from an illness.

132
00:09:43,124 --> 00:09:44,417
After that,

133
00:09:45,084 --> 00:09:47,211
he became like an empty shell.

134
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:50,006
He has been in low spirits,

135
00:09:50,089 --> 00:09:54,385
just spacing out all by himself
inside the house all the time.

136
00:09:56,804 --> 00:09:58,848
My father lives alone, too.

137
00:09:59,849 --> 00:10:04,228
I just can't think of Mr. Susaki's
situation as someone else's business.

138
00:10:10,318 --> 00:10:11,527
Yoshimoto.

139
00:10:13,112 --> 00:10:16,657
Could you go to
Mr. Susaki's apartment for me?

140
00:10:16,741 --> 00:10:17,700
What?

141
00:10:18,784 --> 00:10:20,411
Me?

142
00:10:22,413 --> 00:10:27,418
I believe you will notice things
no one else would.

143
00:10:33,174 --> 00:10:37,053
They say Masumi Mizusawa met with
Shinichi Serizawa from the Shiramine case.

144
00:10:37,136 --> 00:10:39,597
A contact came from the Ministry just now.

145
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:42,808
He also visited Prof. Kujo
a while ago, right?

146
00:10:42,892 --> 00:10:45,186
Is it really safe
to just leave him at large?

147
00:10:46,270 --> 00:10:47,938
Ota.

148
00:10:52,735 --> 00:10:53,569
Yes, sir.

149
00:10:54,528 --> 00:10:56,947
Mizusawa Masumi, was it?

150
00:10:57,823 --> 00:11:00,868
He is a bit of an eyesore, isn't he?

151
00:11:02,036 --> 00:11:03,663
Please take care of it

152
00:11:04,497 --> 00:11:06,582
while we still can.

153
00:11:08,959 --> 00:11:10,169
Understood.

154
00:11:21,889 --> 00:11:24,350
I want to uncover the truth
behind that case.

155
00:11:24,934 --> 00:11:27,269
Stop making a fool out of me.

156
00:11:37,029 --> 00:11:38,072
SUMIRE HOUSE

157
00:11:38,155 --> 00:11:41,283
Do you remember
the last time you saw Mr. Susaki?

158
00:11:41,909 --> 00:11:43,494
I didn't see him.

159
00:11:43,994 --> 00:11:47,164
Mr. Susaki was always behind on his rent.

160
00:11:47,790 --> 00:11:50,126
I came to collect it
at the end of last month.

161
00:11:50,709 --> 00:11:52,711
I rang the bell, and that was it.

162
00:11:52,795 --> 00:11:54,922
Do you remember the exact date?

163
00:11:55,005 --> 00:11:57,174
It was the last Friday of the month.

164
00:11:57,258 --> 00:12:00,302
That's the day
I always come to collect the rent.

165
00:12:00,970 --> 00:12:03,347
It was around the time
of the evening chime.

166
00:12:03,431 --> 00:12:05,474
-Did you notice anything strange?
-No…

167
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:09,311
He didn't respond,
but I heard some rustling from inside.

168
00:12:09,395 --> 00:12:11,397
He must have been in there.

169
00:12:55,316 --> 00:12:56,525
Wow.

170
00:12:57,109 --> 00:12:58,194
What's wrong?

171
00:12:58,277 --> 00:13:01,989
The inside of the refrigerator
is incredibly well-organized.

172
00:13:02,072 --> 00:13:03,949
The seasonings are all there,

173
00:13:04,033 --> 00:13:06,452
and there are plenty
of half-used vegetables too.

174
00:13:06,535 --> 00:13:07,953
You're right.

175
00:13:14,627 --> 00:13:17,713
Igawa, how tall are you?

176
00:13:18,339 --> 00:13:20,132
I'm 168 centimeters.

177
00:13:21,091 --> 00:13:22,510
Can you reach that?

178
00:13:46,158 --> 00:13:47,660
Listen, Yukiko.

179
00:13:48,994 --> 00:13:51,038
On days when something good happens,

180
00:13:51,121 --> 00:13:54,166
you mark it with a red circle like this.

181
00:13:54,667 --> 00:13:55,876
When you do that,

182
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:58,837
it makes you want to fill it
with even more circles,

183
00:13:59,421 --> 00:14:01,006
and even an ordinary day

184
00:14:01,090 --> 00:14:03,342
turns into a good day.

185
00:14:03,425 --> 00:14:04,843
It's true.

186
00:14:06,178 --> 00:14:07,137
Try it.

187
00:14:19,692 --> 00:14:21,235
Are these…

188
00:14:24,947 --> 00:14:28,742
They're supermarket receipts, right?

189
00:14:29,326 --> 00:14:31,412
Can I take these to look into them?

190
00:14:31,996 --> 00:14:32,913
Go ahead.

191
00:14:33,914 --> 00:14:36,750
Recently, we've been getting
attention from the media,

192
00:14:36,834 --> 00:14:40,880
and I feel that MEJ is
becoming better known to the public.

193
00:14:40,963 --> 00:14:42,131
That's why right now--

194
00:14:42,214 --> 00:14:45,175
We have officially decided
to disband the MEJ

195
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:46,635
at the end of this month.

196
00:14:47,261 --> 00:14:48,095
What?

197
00:14:48,178 --> 00:14:52,933
The higher-ups have decided it was
too early to introduce it to Japan.

198
00:14:54,768 --> 00:14:57,813
But it's only been a few months.

199
00:14:59,356 --> 00:15:03,193
Are you actually looking through
the reports we submit every week?

200
00:15:03,277 --> 00:15:05,905
Those were just to gather data.

201
00:15:08,365 --> 00:15:11,535
To decide whether to
officially introduce it or not.

202
00:15:12,828 --> 00:15:14,580
Besides, Dr. Mizusawa…

203
00:15:16,206 --> 00:15:17,708
No, never mind, actually.

204
00:15:19,209 --> 00:15:20,961
But aren't you glad?

205
00:15:21,045 --> 00:15:24,214
Now, you can finally come back.

206
00:15:38,187 --> 00:15:39,939
AUTOPSY REPORT

207
00:15:46,278 --> 00:15:48,197
AUTOPSY REPORT

208
00:16:05,631 --> 00:16:06,924
I'm home!

209
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:10,469
The supermarket was really crowded.

210
00:16:10,970 --> 00:16:15,099
I found an amazing watermelon,
so I bought--

211
00:16:17,434 --> 00:16:18,644
Dad?

212
00:16:19,478 --> 00:16:20,729
Dad!

213
00:16:20,813 --> 00:16:21,855
Dad, are you okay?

214
00:16:23,023 --> 00:16:24,692
Don't be so dramatic.

215
00:16:24,775 --> 00:16:27,069
I just tripped.

216
00:16:27,903 --> 00:16:28,904
Oh, my goodness.

217
00:16:32,741 --> 00:16:34,618
Did you think I had dropped dead?

218
00:16:38,372 --> 00:16:40,082
Oh, that hurts.

219
00:16:45,921 --> 00:16:48,590
The contents of the refrigerator
were well-organized,

220
00:16:48,674 --> 00:16:51,677
and there were plenty
of half-used vegetables and seasonings.

221
00:16:51,760 --> 00:16:52,678
However,

222
00:16:52,761 --> 00:16:57,349
the cooking utensils
were stored quite high up on the shelf.

223
00:16:57,975 --> 00:17:02,146
Igawa, who is 168 centimeters tall,
could barely reach them by jumping.

224
00:17:02,229 --> 00:17:06,275
I think it would be difficult for
Mr. Susaki, who was using a cane,

225
00:17:06,358 --> 00:17:08,610
to get them by himself.

226
00:17:08,694 --> 00:17:10,612
So, in other words…

227
00:17:11,196 --> 00:17:15,325
Mr. Susaki wasn't alone, was he?

228
00:17:20,164 --> 00:17:23,709
We found receipts from shopping
at Super Sakura every Friday.

229
00:17:24,293 --> 00:17:27,713
There are eight receipts in total,
starting from March 13th.

230
00:17:27,796 --> 00:17:33,218
There was a calendar with red circles
marking the same dates as the receipts.

231
00:17:34,053 --> 00:17:37,306
Maybe someone was grocery shopping
for Mr. Susaki, then?

232
00:17:37,389 --> 00:17:40,225
But the note left at Susaki's house said,

233
00:17:40,309 --> 00:17:42,478
"I won't forgive you," right?

234
00:17:42,561 --> 00:17:44,271
Isn't it also possible

235
00:17:44,354 --> 00:17:47,566
that this other person
is the one who killed Susaki?

236
00:17:48,358 --> 00:17:51,236
And then he collapsed
on his way to the front door

237
00:17:51,320 --> 00:17:53,155
seeking help, or something like that.

238
00:17:53,781 --> 00:17:56,658
We are still missing pieces.

239
00:17:59,369 --> 00:18:03,749
We might find something by checking
the supermarket's security cameras.

240
00:18:03,832 --> 00:18:05,501
Right. Let's try it.

241
00:18:05,584 --> 00:18:06,710
Yes.

242
00:18:10,005 --> 00:18:11,924
Mr. Susaki's home is…

243
00:18:13,342 --> 00:18:17,137
His tissue biopsy results
have been sent over.

244
00:18:17,221 --> 00:18:21,350
Let's review the autopsy results
once more.

245
00:18:21,433 --> 00:18:22,810
-Yes.
-Let's check.

246
00:18:26,188 --> 00:18:28,273
SUPERMARKET SAKURA

247
00:18:29,233 --> 00:18:31,819
All right, let's start
with the first one then.

248
00:18:31,902 --> 00:18:32,736
-Okay.
-Okay.

249
00:18:33,612 --> 00:18:35,239
March 13th.

250
00:18:35,322 --> 00:18:38,992
The time on the receipt is 17:24.

251
00:18:39,576 --> 00:18:40,410
Okay.

252
00:18:40,494 --> 00:18:41,620
This one then.

253
00:18:42,454 --> 00:18:43,622
I'll play it.

254
00:18:56,135 --> 00:19:00,055
I'll compare the man in these pictures
against the police database.

255
00:19:00,139 --> 00:19:01,306
Please do.

256
00:19:01,390 --> 00:19:03,308
We'll go do some questioning.

257
00:19:03,392 --> 00:19:04,309
Please.

258
00:19:04,393 --> 00:19:08,647
As expected, there was
contraction band necrosis in the heart.

259
00:19:08,730 --> 00:19:09,940
Which means…

260
00:19:10,023 --> 00:19:13,485
It could be Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

261
00:19:13,569 --> 00:19:14,987
As in, an octopus trap?

262
00:19:15,988 --> 00:19:19,783
It's a heart issue
where the left ventricle weakens

263
00:19:19,867 --> 00:19:22,953
due to severe emotional
or physical stress,

264
00:19:23,036 --> 00:19:26,707
causing the heart
to take the shape of an octopus trap.

265
00:19:26,790 --> 00:19:28,000
True.

266
00:19:28,083 --> 00:19:32,379
That would explain why no other findings
of ischemic heart disease were seen.

267
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:35,257
It's usually transient,

268
00:19:35,340 --> 00:19:38,844
but in severe cases,
fatal examples have been reported.

269
00:19:40,137 --> 00:19:45,517
But what could have been
such a strong stressor for Mr. Susaki?

270
00:19:45,601 --> 00:19:49,313
Does it have something to do with him
heading toward the front door?

271
00:19:54,276 --> 00:19:56,111
AUTOPSY RESULTS REPORT

272
00:20:04,578 --> 00:20:05,829
Hello, sir.

273
00:20:05,913 --> 00:20:08,040
I'm Kiryu from Medical Examiner Japan.

274
00:20:08,123 --> 00:20:10,500
Could you please spare a moment
to speak with me?

275
00:20:11,835 --> 00:20:16,506
I have compiled a review
of our autopsy track record,

276
00:20:16,590 --> 00:20:21,345
along with effective strategies
for cooperating with the police.

277
00:20:21,428 --> 00:20:22,304
Excuse me.

278
00:20:22,387 --> 00:20:24,932
Could you please reconsider
the matter regarding MEJ?

279
00:20:25,515 --> 00:20:26,642
Please.

280
00:20:34,441 --> 00:20:37,027
AUTOPSY RESULTS REPORT

281
00:20:39,738 --> 00:20:42,115
Hey, Kiryu, what are you doing?

282
00:20:43,325 --> 00:20:44,618
I'm sorry.

283
00:20:45,911 --> 00:20:47,037
Mr. Yamazaki.

284
00:20:47,120 --> 00:20:48,872
I just can't give up.

285
00:20:48,956 --> 00:20:50,499
It has already been decided.

286
00:21:02,970 --> 00:21:03,887
Sorry.

287
00:21:03,971 --> 00:21:05,097
Thank you.

288
00:21:13,772 --> 00:21:15,524
Sir, excuse me.

289
00:21:15,607 --> 00:21:16,441
Yes?

290
00:21:16,525 --> 00:21:18,694
Do you make deliveries
to this supermarket every day?

291
00:21:18,777 --> 00:21:19,611
Yes.

292
00:21:19,695 --> 00:21:22,030
Twice a day, in the morning and evening.

293
00:21:23,198 --> 00:21:25,826
Do you recognize
either of these two people?

294
00:21:26,326 --> 00:21:28,036
Oh, this one.

295
00:21:29,705 --> 00:21:31,415
It was about three weeks ago.

296
00:21:31,498 --> 00:21:34,001
I happened to see him
right when I was unloading goods.

297
00:21:36,420 --> 00:21:40,382
The security camera at the supermarket
entrance shows him losing his balance,

298
00:21:40,465 --> 00:21:43,427
and hitting his head on the ground.

299
00:21:43,510 --> 00:21:48,098
So, that means there's no foul play
regarding the injury to his head.

300
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:51,643
Which means Mr. Susaki

301
00:21:51,727 --> 00:21:54,855
passed away from cardiomyopathy
caused by strong stress.

302
00:21:54,938 --> 00:21:58,400
What about the test of the substance
found in the wound on his arm?

303
00:21:59,192 --> 00:22:00,235
Here it is.

304
00:22:03,989 --> 00:22:05,949
Plant fiber…

305
00:22:06,033 --> 00:22:07,617
From the tatami flooring.

306
00:22:07,701 --> 00:22:11,663
It would require a fairly strong force
to result in this kind of injury.

307
00:22:12,289 --> 00:22:15,667
Unable to move due to paralysis
and being weakened,

308
00:22:15,751 --> 00:22:19,755
Mr. Susaki desperately tried to head
toward the front door,

309
00:22:19,838 --> 00:22:24,301
dragging his entire body weight
with his right arm.

310
00:22:34,102 --> 00:22:34,936
Yes?

311
00:22:37,606 --> 00:22:38,690
I'll be right back.

312
00:22:40,067 --> 00:22:41,526
They found the man from the receipt.

313
00:22:41,610 --> 00:22:42,486
What?

314
00:22:42,569 --> 00:22:44,654
He was being held in custody for theft.

315
00:22:59,795 --> 00:23:00,629
Go ahead.

316
00:23:07,219 --> 00:23:08,386
Now then.

317
00:23:08,470 --> 00:23:11,723
Please cooperate with us
to help determine the cause of death.

318
00:23:21,274 --> 00:23:25,278
You are Yasuhiko Hayashida, correct?

319
00:23:27,989 --> 00:23:28,907
Who are you?

320
00:23:30,325 --> 00:23:35,455
My name is Masumi Mizusawa
from Medical Examiner Japan.

321
00:23:37,541 --> 00:23:38,834
Excuse me…

322
00:23:40,836 --> 00:23:43,839
but did you know Hideo Susaki?

323
00:23:48,760 --> 00:23:51,763
Did something happen to Mr. Susaki?

324
00:23:55,308 --> 00:23:56,560
He passed away.

325
00:24:02,315 --> 00:24:06,736
Could you tell me
what kind of relationship you had

326
00:24:07,696 --> 00:24:09,781
with Mr. Susaki?

327
00:24:16,413 --> 00:24:17,455
I…

328
00:24:19,583 --> 00:24:21,960
used to get in trouble a lot
when I was young.

329
00:24:24,588 --> 00:24:26,715
I was in prison for a while.

330
00:24:30,260 --> 00:24:33,847
I wanted to do honest work once I got out,

331
00:24:35,849 --> 00:24:38,768
but no company wanted to hire
someone like me.

332
00:24:40,687 --> 00:24:43,064
So I only had cheap day-labor gigs.

333
00:24:43,815 --> 00:24:44,774
And…

334
00:24:46,484 --> 00:24:48,570
when I ran out of money,
I would do it again,

335
00:24:50,113 --> 00:24:52,032
get caught, and repeat the cycle.

336
00:24:54,701 --> 00:24:55,911
Pretty pathetic, right?

337
00:24:58,622 --> 00:25:00,665
<i>I wasn't even there when my parents died.</i>

338
00:25:02,542 --> 00:25:04,252
<i>Because I was in prison.</i>

339
00:25:11,760 --> 00:25:13,970
SALARY

340
00:25:29,152 --> 00:25:30,820
<i>About three months ago,</i>

341
00:25:31,863 --> 00:25:34,574
<i>I snuck into Mr. Susaki's apartment.</i>

342
00:26:46,396 --> 00:26:47,856
You need money, don't you?

343
00:27:05,123 --> 00:27:06,416
What the hell?

344
00:27:10,253 --> 00:27:13,340
Can you… cook?

345
00:27:14,883 --> 00:27:15,925
What?

346
00:27:17,427 --> 00:27:19,262
With that 30,000 yen,

347
00:27:19,846 --> 00:27:21,765
make me some food, would you?

348
00:27:24,684 --> 00:27:27,020
You can keep all the change.

349
00:27:30,815 --> 00:27:32,150
<i>I don't really know why,</i>

350
00:27:33,443 --> 00:27:36,404
<i>but he just reminded me of my father.</i>

351
00:27:37,864 --> 00:27:40,200
<i>I should have just</i>
<i>taken the money and ran.</i>

352
00:27:44,579 --> 00:27:46,956
<i>Before I knew it,</i>
<i>I was going shopping for him.</i>

353
00:27:48,291 --> 00:27:54,255
CARROTS FROM CHIBA, 98 YEN
CARROTS FROM TOKUSHIMA, 118 YEN

354
00:28:01,513 --> 00:28:03,390
APARTMENT 101 - SUSAKI

355
00:28:09,771 --> 00:28:10,939
Curry, huh?

356
00:28:12,941 --> 00:28:14,442
Is that a problem?

357
00:28:15,819 --> 00:28:17,237
You eat some too.

358
00:28:22,033 --> 00:28:23,118
Let's eat.

359
00:28:57,652 --> 00:28:58,528
What?

360
00:29:01,906 --> 00:29:03,116
You didn't run away.

361
00:29:10,999 --> 00:29:11,833
Hey.

362
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:15,086
Can you cook next week, too?

363
00:29:15,712 --> 00:29:16,838
What?

364
00:29:16,921 --> 00:29:18,381
I'll give you 30,000 yen.

365
00:29:25,346 --> 00:29:26,931
<i>Every Friday…</i>

366
00:29:27,015 --> 00:29:28,683
-Thank you very much.
-Thank you.

367
00:29:29,267 --> 00:29:32,604
<i>…cooking for Mr. Susaki became the norm.</i>

368
00:29:33,772 --> 00:29:34,689
<i>I actually</i>

369
00:29:36,107 --> 00:29:38,067
<i>really started looking forward to it.</i>

370
00:30:01,007 --> 00:30:02,842
I heard you on the first ring.

371
00:30:06,095 --> 00:30:07,514
Coming, coming.

372
00:30:14,646 --> 00:30:15,480
Hey.

373
00:30:18,107 --> 00:30:18,942
Hello.

374
00:30:21,528 --> 00:30:23,321
I would have preferred omurice.

375
00:30:26,825 --> 00:30:27,826
I didn't get eggs.

376
00:30:37,752 --> 00:30:39,045
I'll put it in the fridge.

377
00:30:39,671 --> 00:30:40,505
Thanks.

378
00:31:10,368 --> 00:31:12,662
The thing I made the other day
was good, right?

379
00:31:12,745 --> 00:31:14,122
Not particularly.

380
00:31:28,553 --> 00:31:30,054
Buy a phone at least.

381
00:31:32,265 --> 00:31:33,808
I have no one to talk to.

382
00:31:35,602 --> 00:31:36,603
Any family?

383
00:31:36,686 --> 00:31:37,687
No.

384
00:31:38,438 --> 00:31:39,397
Same here.

385
00:31:42,525 --> 00:31:44,986
Bet you don't want to be similar
to a criminal.

386
00:31:46,988 --> 00:31:49,782
The food you make is delicious.

387
00:31:54,329 --> 00:31:56,873
You can still start over.

388
00:32:01,544 --> 00:32:02,587
So,

389
00:32:03,588 --> 00:32:05,340
never commit a crime again.

390
00:32:12,513 --> 00:32:13,348
Okay.

391
00:32:30,406 --> 00:32:32,033
<i>But I couldn't do it.</i>

392
00:32:32,116 --> 00:32:33,952
<i>No matter how much I worked,</i>

393
00:32:34,452 --> 00:32:36,204
<i>or how much money Mr. Susaki gave me,</i>

394
00:32:36,996 --> 00:32:38,957
<i>I ran out of money again.</i>

395
00:32:40,208 --> 00:32:41,376
<i>And I…</i>

396
00:33:05,108 --> 00:33:06,401
Mr. Susaki said…

397
00:33:09,612 --> 00:33:11,614
that if I ever did it again…

398
00:33:14,158 --> 00:33:16,953
he would never forgive me.

399
00:33:21,082 --> 00:33:22,166
That's why…

400
00:33:23,710 --> 00:33:25,753
I couldn't bring myself to face him.

401
00:33:29,132 --> 00:33:30,508
There were red circles…

402
00:33:32,552 --> 00:33:34,554
on his calendar.

403
00:33:36,222 --> 00:33:37,390
Red circles?

404
00:33:39,100 --> 00:33:42,103
If they were for the days
you were scheduled to come,

405
00:33:42,812 --> 00:33:47,150
then there should have been a circle
on the coming Friday as well.

406
00:33:49,736 --> 00:33:50,737
But…

407
00:33:51,904 --> 00:33:53,948
Mr. Susaki drew them

408
00:33:55,324 --> 00:33:59,328
after you had already visited him.

409
00:34:01,414 --> 00:34:03,082
I think for Mr. Susaki…

410
00:34:04,792 --> 00:34:06,544
the days you visited

411
00:34:07,503 --> 00:34:09,338
were good days.

412
00:34:51,380 --> 00:34:52,215
Hey.

413
00:34:52,882 --> 00:34:54,842
Watch where you're going, gramps.

414
00:34:54,926 --> 00:34:55,968
Watch it.

415
00:34:57,053 --> 00:34:58,137
Got it?

416
00:34:58,221 --> 00:35:00,098
Come on, that's enough.

417
00:35:17,448 --> 00:35:19,784
On the Friday you didn't come,

418
00:35:20,785 --> 00:35:23,913
Mr. Susaki went to the supermarket
by himself.

419
00:35:25,248 --> 00:35:26,249
What?

420
00:35:27,458 --> 00:35:30,545
I think he might have gone
to look for you.

421
00:35:33,673 --> 00:35:35,299
And we suspect

422
00:35:36,134 --> 00:35:38,761
that when he hit his head that time,

423
00:35:38,845 --> 00:35:42,431
it caused a subdural hematoma to form.

424
00:35:44,433 --> 00:35:49,522
Mr. Susaki's symptoms also progressed
without him realizing it,

425
00:35:49,605 --> 00:35:51,691
<i>gradually losing his physical freedom,</i>

426
00:35:51,774 --> 00:35:53,025
<i>and in the end,</i>

427
00:35:53,109 --> 00:35:56,612
<i>he became unable to move</i>
<i>even a single step.</i>

428
00:35:59,240 --> 00:36:00,950
Wait a second.

429
00:36:04,495 --> 00:36:05,621
That means…

430
00:36:08,624 --> 00:36:09,876
it's my fault…

431
00:36:13,588 --> 00:36:14,881
that Mr. Susaki…

432
00:36:26,225 --> 00:36:27,685
Every Friday…

433
00:36:31,189 --> 00:36:33,691
right when the evening chime rang…

434
00:36:37,028 --> 00:36:39,780
I would open the front door
of Mr. Susaki's house.

435
00:36:45,828 --> 00:36:48,247
Even now, when I hear that sound,

436
00:36:49,624 --> 00:36:51,125
I remember Mr. Susaki's face.

437
00:36:57,506 --> 00:36:58,549
Mr. Susaki…

438
00:37:00,468 --> 00:37:01,385
I'm…

439
00:37:05,056 --> 00:37:06,098
sorry.

440
00:37:14,357 --> 00:37:16,567
I believe the cause of Mr. Susaki's death

441
00:37:16,651 --> 00:37:20,655
was indeed Takotsubo cardiomyopathy.

442
00:37:24,075 --> 00:37:27,745
It is a disease that often develops
when triggered

443
00:37:27,828 --> 00:37:29,872
by intense emotional stress.

444
00:37:32,333 --> 00:37:37,004
The intense stress for Mr. Susaki
might have been

445
00:37:38,297 --> 00:37:43,761
the fact that he would no longer
be able to meet you.

446
00:38:17,253 --> 00:38:19,088
Damn it!

447
00:38:22,383 --> 00:38:23,384
Damn.

448
00:38:23,467 --> 00:38:24,468
I WON'T FORGIVE YOU

449
00:39:44,799 --> 00:39:46,550
So annoying.

450
00:39:47,259 --> 00:39:49,136
I heard you on the first ring.

451
00:39:54,809 --> 00:39:56,018
Mr. Susaki?

452
00:39:56,936 --> 00:39:58,979
Pay the rent already!

453
00:40:31,971 --> 00:40:33,389
I'm the worst.

454
00:40:36,767 --> 00:40:37,768
Why…

455
00:40:40,813 --> 00:40:42,314
Why would he want me to…

456
00:40:43,983 --> 00:40:45,276
I think Mr. Susaki

457
00:40:46,652 --> 00:40:47,945
wanted you

458
00:40:48,737 --> 00:40:51,198
to come see him again, Mr. Hayashida.

459
00:42:06,857 --> 00:42:08,609
The days I came here…

460
00:42:11,320 --> 00:42:13,239
<i>On days when something good happens,</i>

461
00:42:13,322 --> 00:42:16,700
<i>you mark it with a red circle like this.</i>

462
00:42:25,334 --> 00:42:27,586
You don't need to come anymore.

463
00:42:31,715 --> 00:42:32,633
Hey.

464
00:42:33,133 --> 00:42:34,510
Are you listening?

465
00:42:35,511 --> 00:42:37,346
Stop coming.

466
00:42:44,186 --> 00:42:45,479
Dad.

467
00:42:48,649 --> 00:42:50,025
I'll come by again.

468
00:43:16,969 --> 00:43:18,804
What are you smiling about?

469
00:43:21,640 --> 00:43:24,977
I've taught my dad
how to use a messaging app.

470
00:43:25,477 --> 00:43:26,520
GOOD MORNING (SMILE)
TAKECA, TAKE CAR

471
00:43:26,604 --> 00:43:27,688
He types a lot!

472
00:43:28,772 --> 00:43:30,149
Your dad is cute.

473
00:43:30,232 --> 00:43:31,191
Is he?

474
00:43:31,275 --> 00:43:32,401
May I show them?

475
00:43:33,027 --> 00:43:34,153
Look at this.

476
00:43:35,112 --> 00:43:37,364
-Your dad?
-He spelled it all wrong.

477
00:43:37,448 --> 00:43:39,366
He tried to send it a few times.

478
00:43:40,743 --> 00:43:42,036
That's cute.

479
00:43:42,786 --> 00:43:44,496
He can't type it right.

480
00:43:48,125 --> 00:43:49,251
Excuse me.

481
00:43:50,753 --> 00:43:53,589
I have something to tell you all.

482
00:44:00,179 --> 00:44:01,680
MEJ…

483
00:44:07,645 --> 00:44:11,857
MEJ will be shut down
by the end of this month.

484
00:44:23,452 --> 00:44:25,871
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.
